<p><br>
</p>
<p>A Journey Without a Map: Writing Poetry</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>(Offered by K. Srilata)</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>This day-long workshop is designed to introduce participants to the form=
 and practice of poetry.&nbsp; A central goal of this workshop is to help d=
evelop greater ease with the process of writing poetry. Through interactive=
 sessions, close reading, writing exercises
 and feedback sessions, participants will discover the answers to some of t=
hese questions:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Where do we look for our material?&nbsp; How do we train the eye? </p>
<p>How should we work with emotion, image, rhyme and rhythm to create a poe=
m?&nbsp; Are metre and rhyme essential to poetry?
</p>
<p>How do we lineate a poem?&nbsp; </p>
<p>How do we choose a poetic form? </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Pre-requisites: A strong interest in writing. Ages: 18 and above. Maximu=
m number of participants: 20
</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>About K. Srilata:<br>
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:justify">K. Srilata is Professor of English at IIT M=
adras. Her books include four poetry collections:
<em>Bookmarking the Oasis. </em><em>Writing Octopus,</em> <em>Arriving Shor=
tly</em> and
<em>Seablue Child</em>, a novel <em>Table for Four, </em>long listed in 200=
9 for the Man Asian literary prize and published by Penguin, two co-edited =
anthologies
<em>The</em> <em>Rapids of a Great River: The Penguin Book of Tamil Poetry =
</em>and
<em>Short Fiction from South India</em> (OUP), a translation of R. Vatsala&=
#8217;s Tamil novel
<em>Once there was a girl</em> (<em>Vattathul</em>) and a translation of wo=
men&#8217;s writing from the Self-Respect movement
<em>The Other Half of the Coconut: Women Writing Self-Respect History</em> =
(Zubaan). Srilata has been a writer-in-residence at the University of Stirl=
ing, at Sangam house and at the Yeonhui Art Space in Seoul. She co-curates =
the CMI Arts Initiative along with
 Madhavan Mukund and K.V. Subrahmanyam.</p>
